data.value:
Neptune is the eighth planet from the sun, and the first planet to get its existence predicted by mathematical calculations before it was actually seen through a telescope. Like earth, Neptune has a rocky core, but it has a much thicker atmosphere that prohibits the existence of life as we know it. This cloud cover is a vivid blue tint, which is partially due to an unknown compound and the result of the absorption of red light by the planet's hydrogen and helium atmosphere. Under its atmosphere, it possesses a thick, slushy fluid mix of water, ammonia and methane ices.
Neptune has 14 known moons, all of which are named after lesser sea gods and nymphs from Greek mythology. The largest of its moons is Triton, as well as being the only one of Neptune’s moons that’s spherical in shape.
Neptune’s winds can reach up to 1,500mph, the fastest detected so far in the solar system. By studying cloud formations on the gas giant, scientists are able to calculate that a day on Neptune lasts just under sixteen hours. Neptune’s orbit takes roughly 165 years. This means that Neptune completes its first orbit since being discovered in 1846 back in 2011. Neptune is named after the Roman god of the sea, who’s Greek name is Poseidon.
